&NewLine;

**Affable apes live longer, study shows**

&NewLine;

Male chimps that are less aggressive and form strong social bonds tend to live longer, research suggests.

&NewLine;

A study of hundreds of captive chimpanzees showed that males that [SELECT id=99] 3 p. – by being sensitive, protective and cooperative – outlived their less amiable peers.

The team, led by researchers at the University of Edinburgh, found that, contrary to studies of humans and other primates, [SELECT id=100] 3 p. had no impact on chimpanzees’ longevity.

&NewLine;

Extraversion is frequently associated with longer life in other nonhuman primates, while conscientiousness and neuroticism are associated with longer and shorter life, respectively, in humans.

&NewLine;

Using personality and survival data from 538 chimpanzees – our closest ape relative – the study tested [SELECT id=101] 3 p. were associated with longevity.

&NewLine;

Results suggest that amongst male chimps, evolution has favoured those that are more agreeable.

&NewLine;

Researchers also found some evidence that female chimps [SELECT id=102] 3 p. – those who more readily explored and adapted to changes in their physical and social environments – were more likely to live longer.

&NewLine;

The researchers, including colleagues from the US and Japan, assessed chimps’ personalities based on a questionnaire of common adjectives and chimpanzee behaviours completed by keepers and researchers who worked with these animals for between seven and 24 years.

&NewLine;

The chimps lived in zoos, research facilities and sanctuaries located in the UK, US, Netherlands, Australia and Japan.

&NewLine;

The findings suggest that links between personality and lifespan in people may not be entirely explained by inherent characteristics, [SELECT id=103] 3 p.. Drew Altschul from the University of Edinburgh said: “Studying the personality of chimps – one of our closest biological relatives – suggests that the quality of our social relationships can significantly impact our lives.”

